Description: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a convex side like from a bag or a vessel, several impressions of string in the break with a width of 0.3 cm. The front side is concave and several cracks are visible. It shows an impression of an oval scarab-like seal. The motif shows a kneeling figure at the right, facing to the left with a bow in one hand and the second arm in a raised posture, with a second line. To the left of the figure part of a cartouche that seems to be mn-mAa.t-[R'].
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Amara West (Nubia), E14.7 temple magazine
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
